WEBVTT

00:12.080 --> 00:14.151
WOMAN: (SINGING) Mama,
can I, huh? Mama, can I, huh, huh?

00:14.280 --> 00:17.432
Can I, Mama, won't you please
let me? Mama, can I, huh?

00:21.680 --> 00:24.035
That's the sweetest little dress,
Sally Where'd you get the pattern?

00:24.120 --> 00:26.760
Made me one just like it
out of yellow dotted Swiss

00:31.440 --> 00:33.795
Yes, I guess we got the
earliest garden in the county

00:33.880 --> 00:36.998
Beneath the strawberries are
a heap of snappin' green beans

00:37.240 --> 00:39.436
Too bad about your boy

00:41.360 --> 00:43.431
Mama, make Willie
quit pulling at my hair

00:43.560 --> 00:45.949
Mama, ouch! Ouch!
Mama, just make Willie quit it

00:46.240 --> 00:48.390
Tommy, if ya
don't put down that stick

00:48.480 --> 00:50.756
I'm gonna wear you
out with it Boy, be quick

00:50.840 --> 00:53.434
Come quick, Sammy Jean
stuck her finger in a Coke bottle

00:53.520 --> 00:55.557
Can't get it out 'cause
it's stuck, stuck, stuck

00:55.640 --> 00:57.950
Now I told you my mama
didn't raise no fool

00:58.040 --> 01:00.680
I can do anything
if I got the right tools

01:00.760 --> 01:02.797
Mama, can I, huh?
Mama, can I, huh, huh?

01:02.880 --> 01:05.394
Can I, Mama, won't you please
let me? Mama, can I, huh?

01:06.000 --> 01:07.752
(DOGS BARKING IN DISTANCE)

01:12.560 --> 01:13.834
(HORSE NEIGHS)

01:19.440 --> 01:20.839
(ROOSTER CROWING)

01:22.200 --> 01:24.157
(GRINDING)

01:36.960 --> 01:38.871
(KIDS CHATTERING)

01:46.400 --> 01:48.277
(CURRENCY COUNTER WHIRRING)

01:49.680 --> 01:50.954
(COUNTER BEEPS)

01:51.360 --> 01:53.510
CHARLIE: Jeremy Kleiner up
in Winnipeg writes,

01:56.520 --> 01:58.909
"Feel better, boss man."
That's nice.

02:00.880 --> 02:02.359
And then,

02:06.520 --> 02:08.157
Carter Bunch says,

02:08.240 --> 02:10.880
"Keep fightin', you old cuss.
You'll outlive us all."

02:21.200 --> 02:22.952
Indian Joe sent porn.

02:27.880 --> 02:30.554
Give these to the Chinaman.
The usual disbursement.

02:39.760 --> 02:41.194
(WHISPERING)

02:51.320 --> 02:53.311
Get your dad and uncles.

02:53.440 --> 02:54.635
We need to talk.

02:56.480 --> 02:57.675
(GRINDING)

03:03.920 --> 03:05.354
You finish your chores?

03:05.440 --> 03:07.556
Yes, sir. Been helpin'
Grandma with the bank.

03:07.640 --> 03:11.156
She sent me to get you. Wants
us all together up in the house.

03:12.360 --> 03:13.589
Dodd's inside.

03:17.320 --> 03:18.833
DODD: ...fought in
the trenches in France.

03:19.920 --> 03:21.115
World War I.

03:21.960 --> 03:24.600
He was an Artillerieschiitzen,
my grandad, a gunner.

03:25.440 --> 03:28.034
Blasted mustard
gas at the Allies.

03:28.120 --> 03:30.680
Had 'em dancing
like poisoned rats.

03:31.800 --> 03:33.791
The Brits
caught him in a raid,

03:33.880 --> 03:36.872
hung him by his thumbs
for six days straight,

03:36.960 --> 03:39.839
so this, what we're doin',
this is nothin'.

03:41.160 --> 03:42.719
Are you listening to me?

03:43.480 --> 03:44.879
Is he listening to me?

03:46.480 --> 03:47.595
Cut off his ears.

03:50.360 --> 03:51.589
DODD: Wake him up.

03:53.400 --> 03:55.437
He's dead, I think.

03:57.240 --> 03:58.310
Weak.

04:01.520 --> 04:02.635
CHARLIE: Uncle Dodd?

04:05.160 --> 04:07.117
Doc's finished.
Grandma wants us.

04:58.720 --> 05:00.040
(CAR DOORS OPENING)

05:01.800 --> 05:03.359
(ENGINE STARTING)

05:04.080 --> 05:05.434
(DOORS CLOSING)

05:09.920 --> 05:11.399
Who were the goons?

05:13.800 --> 05:14.870
Kansas City.

05:16.000 --> 05:17.559
They wanna buy us out.

05:17.640 --> 05:19.199
So they came to you, then?

05:20.360 --> 05:22.317
They came to see your father.
But he's not well.

05:22.400 --> 05:24.676
So they talked to
me as a surrogate.

05:24.800 --> 05:25.995
I should have been there.

05:26.080 --> 05:28.674
Jeez, Dad.
Don't be such a baby.

05:28.760 --> 05:29.830
Shut up.

05:29.920 --> 05:31.319
She shouldn't be in here.

05:32.200 --> 05:34.840
She's old enough.
I told her to stay.

05:34.920 --> 05:36.069
She's a girl.

05:36.720 --> 05:38.552
And girls grow up
to be women,

05:39.960 --> 05:41.712
and change boys' diapers.

05:45.800 --> 05:47.552
Where's your little brother?

05:47.640 --> 05:49.995
Rye? Haven't seen him.

05:50.080 --> 05:53.118
Who knows with that kid?
Probably neck deep in some pussy.

05:53.720 --> 05:54.790
With a girl, you know.

05:55.320 --> 05:56.469
What's the offer?

05:57.400 --> 05:59.118
He talks to you.
Where is he?

06:00.120 --> 06:03.556
Said he had things
to do out of town.

06:03.640 --> 06:05.392
SIMONE: I saw him yesterday.
FLOYD: What things?

06:05.800 --> 06:06.790
What's the offer?

06:09.240 --> 06:11.072
The world's
becoming more corporate.

06:11.160 --> 06:12.719
This was their pitch to me.

06:14.440 --> 06:17.432
And in this new world there's
no room for family business.

06:17.560 --> 06:18.755
So, war.

06:23.280 --> 06:25.920
They're offering to buy
the whole operation,

06:26.000 --> 06:27.320
then pay us to run it.

06:27.960 --> 06:29.030
Bottom line?

06:29.120 --> 06:31.714
Bottom line, very little
changes on the ground.

06:32.920 --> 06:34.319
We may actually earn more.

06:35.160 --> 06:38.073
But instead of running it,
we report to them.

06:38.160 --> 06:39.912
To who?
Kansas City.

06:40.040 --> 06:41.474
Balls. What'd you say?

06:42.040 --> 06:44.600
I said thank you very much,
I'll consult with my partners.

06:44.680 --> 06:45.875
Meaning, Grandpa.

06:47.000 --> 06:48.035
No.

06:48.640 --> 06:49.755
The stroke.

06:51.360 --> 06:53.397
Your father is not
in a lucid state.

06:54.720 --> 06:58.714
Nor will he be,
possibly ever.

06:59.320 --> 07:00.594
What are you saying?

07:01.000 --> 07:02.832
I'm saying your grandpa
built this business,

07:02.920 --> 07:05.036
but he's no longer
capable of running it.

07:09.000 --> 07:11.310
We should have
a moment of silence, maybe.

07:15.640 --> 07:16.596
As new boss,

07:16.680 --> 07:19.320
I say we tell these
Kansas City schwanzes

07:19.400 --> 07:20.470
to go to hell
in the fast lane.

07:20.560 --> 07:21.595
Now, hold on.

07:21.680 --> 07:23.034
DODD: What, you think
it should be you?

07:23.120 --> 07:24.349
No, stupid.

07:24.440 --> 07:25.430
Mom.

07:25.520 --> 07:27.193
Boss can't be a woman!

07:29.960 --> 07:31.314
Who says?

07:32.000 --> 07:33.195
Think about it.

07:34.440 --> 07:36.351
Mom's the one with
ties to Winnipeg.

07:37.240 --> 07:39.959
History with Carter B
and the Solkerk crew.

07:40.040 --> 07:41.553
Suppliers trust her.

07:42.320 --> 07:43.549
It should be Mom.

07:43.640 --> 07:45.916
Hell, yes.
I vote for Grandma.

07:46.000 --> 07:48.071
Shut up.
We're not voting.

07:49.480 --> 07:50.914
I'm oldest.

07:52.280 --> 07:53.554
I'm boss.

07:56.560 --> 07:57.914
End of story.

08:02.280 --> 08:03.679
Give us a minute.

08:10.360 --> 08:11.759
Not you.

08:17.080 --> 08:18.115
Sit.

08:18.840 --> 08:20.035
Eat somethin'.

08:21.640 --> 08:22.630
(DOORS CLOSE)

08:47.560 --> 08:48.595
This moment,

08:50.960 --> 08:53.110
how things go in
the next few weeks,

08:53.800 --> 08:54.790
will decide...

08:54.880 --> 08:56.917
That's why...
Let me finish!

09:03.560 --> 09:04.789
(EXHALES)

09:10.920 --> 09:15.232
Your grandfather left the
ashes of the Weimar Republic

09:15.320 --> 09:17.960
and came to this country
to build a name for himself.

09:19.520 --> 09:20.954
He built an empire

09:22.240 --> 09:23.799
from a shoe shine box,

09:26.320 --> 09:29.995
and then and only then
did he send for your father.

09:31.400 --> 09:32.913
Ma. I know the story.

09:33.000 --> 09:34.991
No. You don't.

09:38.320 --> 09:41.995
"Cause if you did, you'd know
that you are just a small part of it.

09:42.920 --> 09:44.593
That's what an empire is.

09:45.520 --> 09:47.033
It's bigger than any son.

09:48.000 --> 09:49.149
Or daughter.

09:53.000 --> 09:54.115
Eat.

09:56.040 --> 09:57.155
I'm not hungry.

09:57.280 --> 09:59.556
I'm your mother,
you will eat with me.

10:01.640 --> 10:02.835
(SIGHS)

10:10.840 --> 10:12.069
Your time will come.

10:13.520 --> 10:14.510
It will.

10:15.560 --> 10:16.994
But this isn't it.

10:18.440 --> 10:20.192
And if you stand by me now,

10:20.960 --> 10:24.112
I promise you that as
soon as this crisis is over,

10:24.200 --> 10:26.191
I'll hand you your legacy

10:26.840 --> 10:29.036
and I'll turn my
thoughts to the grave.

10:34.400 --> 10:36.755
Now, we need to find Rye.

10:36.840 --> 10:37.955
Can you do that for me?

10:38.040 --> 10:39.075
Yes, ma'am.

10:39.160 --> 10:41.754
Wherever he is,
whatever he's doing,

10:42.840 --> 10:43.875
bring him home.

11:03.200 --> 11:05.077
If you were
a betting man, I'm sayin'.

11:05.160 --> 11:06.753
Well, I think history
has proven

11:06.840 --> 11:10.390
people of the Germanic
persuasion don't surrender easy.

11:11.040 --> 11:12.678
But you can kill 'em.

11:12.760 --> 11:15.798
Unless the woman,
being a woman...

11:16.920 --> 11:18.035
Maybe we can scare her.

11:19.960 --> 11:20.995
No.

11:21.080 --> 11:23.435
I think we cut a deal
with one of the sons.

11:24.400 --> 11:26.277
The youngest maybe, Rye.

11:27.280 --> 11:28.429
The elders are...

11:29.480 --> 11:34.429
Well, you know how a lobster's got
a pincher claw and a crusher claw?

11:38.400 --> 11:39.595
Which one's which?

11:39.680 --> 11:40.670
Pardon?

11:41.360 --> 11:44.193
Which son is which claw?

11:44.280 --> 11:45.714
You know what?
Forget it.

11:45.800 --> 11:48.599
I don't want anything to do
with your fakakta metaphor.

11:49.600 --> 11:53.309
Management says acquire
the territory, we acquire it.

11:53.400 --> 11:56.472
Whether that's cash down or
sending bodies to the morgue,

11:56.560 --> 11:58.517
that's up to the krauts.

11:59.480 --> 12:02.916
First Gerhardt to switch sides
gets a shiny red apple.

12:11.160 --> 12:12.309
RECEPTIONIST: No, I know.

12:13.000 --> 12:13.990
I know. Uh-huh.

12:15.800 --> 12:18.030
No, no. Sheriff says
it's a local matter.

12:18.640 --> 12:20.039
Yeah.

12:21.040 --> 12:22.030
Okay then.

12:22.640 --> 12:23.630
Yeah.

12:29.160 --> 12:31.071
(TYPING IN THE BACKGROUND)

12:44.080 --> 12:45.309
(CHAIR CREAKS)

12:45.520 --> 12:47.238
(PHONE RINGS)

12:51.680 --> 12:53.432
(CHILDREN PLAYING)

12:53.520 --> 12:55.352
(DOG BARKING)

12:57.360 --> 12:59.397
(CAR STEREO MUSIC PLAYING)

13:03.040 --> 13:04.189
MOLLY: Papa.
HANK: That's me.

13:04.280 --> 13:05.270
Papa!

13:05.360 --> 13:06.839
Did you get some sleep?

13:08.320 --> 13:10.630
Uh... A couple hours,
you know. Went pretty late.

13:10.720 --> 13:11.790
MOLLY: Papa. Papa.
HANK: What? What?

13:11.880 --> 13:13.359
What can I make you?

13:13.440 --> 13:15.670
Uh, eggs would be good,
if not a bother.

13:16.360 --> 13:19.318
I could do oatmeal, maybe.

13:19.440 --> 13:20.430
Tell me a story.

13:20.520 --> 13:22.158
Somethin' about
the smell of eggs right now...

13:22.240 --> 13:23.674
Okay, coffee's fine.

13:25.120 --> 13:26.110
Uh...

13:26.640 --> 13:28.517
Okay. (SIGHS)

13:29.240 --> 13:31.550
Once upon a time
there was an oyster.

13:31.640 --> 13:32.675
MOLLY: What's an oyster?

13:32.760 --> 13:34.159
It's a shellfish.

13:34.240 --> 13:35.310
MOLLY: Fish?

13:35.400 --> 13:36.993
Close enough.
Lou sleepin'?

13:37.080 --> 13:39.549
BETSY: He had a call with
the brass. Should be down soon.

13:40.920 --> 13:43.070
Apparently, one of
your victims was a judge.

13:43.400 --> 13:45.073
A judge, huh?
BETSY: Uh-huh.

13:46.320 --> 13:47.390
The older woman?

13:47.960 --> 13:49.075
Out of North Dakota.

13:50.680 --> 13:51.670
Huh.

13:51.800 --> 13:52.835
Papa!

13:52.920 --> 13:54.354
Hello. Yes.

13:54.440 --> 13:55.760
What's the story?

13:55.840 --> 13:57.160
What story?

13:57.240 --> 13:58.799
About the oyster.

13:58.880 --> 13:59.870
Oh, uh...

13:59.960 --> 14:01.030
Yeah.

14:01.120 --> 14:02.440
Sorry.
Lieutenant called.

14:03.240 --> 14:04.310
Judge, huh?

14:04.880 --> 14:06.359
Betsy told you.
HANK: Yeah.

14:06.440 --> 14:08.670
Yeah, municipal
judge up in Fargo.

14:08.880 --> 14:10.234
Huh. Oh, yeah.

14:11.040 --> 14:13.839
One day, the oyster
got caught in the net.

14:14.400 --> 14:16.596
Fisherman pulled him up,
all set to eat him.

14:17.440 --> 14:20.432
Except he happened to have
his daughter in the boat.

14:20.520 --> 14:21.715
And she said...

14:21.800 --> 14:23.871
"Daddy, how would you feel

14:23.960 --> 14:26.474
"if I peeled the roof off
your house and ate you?"

14:27.600 --> 14:28.795
Was that you?

14:29.720 --> 14:30.710
It was.

14:31.160 --> 14:32.833
That's the story of
how your mom and me

14:32.920 --> 14:35.275
came to eat hot dogs
for dinner, once again.

14:35.360 --> 14:36.350
BETSY: Mmm-hmm.

14:36.440 --> 14:39.034
Hey, so knowing she's a judge,
that change anything?

14:39.120 --> 14:42.033
Well, you know, I guess
we gotta ask ourselves,

14:42.800 --> 14:45.269
was this judge just in the
wrong place at the wrong time,

14:45.400 --> 14:48.040
or was this
whole mess about her?

15:59.600 --> 16:00.590
(SPLASHES)

16:02.680 --> 16:03.715
Gonna be late
for work, huh?

16:07.400 --> 16:09.550
Yeah, I don't think
I'm goin' in today.

16:10.320 --> 16:12.709
Well, gotta keep up
appearances though, right?

16:12.800 --> 16:13.995
You said.

16:14.680 --> 16:16.159
Jeez, hon, your eye...

16:16.240 --> 16:19.392
No, it doesn't hurt.
It just... It looks bad.

16:21.240 --> 16:22.878
Maybe I should
stay home too.

16:23.000 --> 16:24.513
No. You should go.

16:25.440 --> 16:27.875
Just tell them you hit
your head or something.

16:27.960 --> 16:29.075
I gotta...

16:30.120 --> 16:32.509
There's too much
stuff to do here.

16:32.600 --> 16:33.874
I...

16:33.960 --> 16:37.271
Car's gotta be cleaned,
the floors.

16:38.160 --> 16:39.434
I mean...

16:42.720 --> 16:43.835
Yeah.

17:07.960 --> 17:09.030
(DOOR OPENS)

17:17.079 --> 17:18.434
Are you with me?

17:19.640 --> 17:20.710
Good.

17:21.319 --> 17:23.880
Bear's thrown in with Momma.
That's his loss.

17:24.880 --> 17:27.348
Distributors will stand
with me, if I press.

17:27.480 --> 17:28.709
But we need Rye.

17:29.440 --> 17:31.875
So, when you find him, you bring
him to me first, you understand?

17:31.960 --> 17:33.439
Not her. Me.

18:12.480 --> 18:13.515
There you go.

18:14.720 --> 18:16.119
Thanks.

18:16.200 --> 18:18.714
Remember to cook them
all the way through this time.

18:19.440 --> 18:20.555
Oh. Thank you.
Hey there, Peggy.

18:20.640 --> 18:21.675
Hey.

18:21.760 --> 18:22.955
Expecting your husband.

18:23.440 --> 18:24.589
Yeah, he had...

18:24.680 --> 18:27.798
At dinner last night,
I think it was some bad clams.

18:27.880 --> 18:29.200
You know, from a can.

18:30.200 --> 18:32.555
Never trust anything
that comes from the sea.

18:32.640 --> 18:34.039
We came from the sea.

18:35.520 --> 18:37.033
Tomorrow, for sure.

18:37.120 --> 18:38.155
Okay.

18:38.240 --> 18:39.560
PEGGY: Bye.
Bye.

18:43.120 --> 18:45.191
...a desperado, I heard.

18:45.280 --> 18:47.556
But Sheriff
thinks a pair of 'em

18:47.640 --> 18:49.677
gunned down those poor people
at the Waffle Hut

18:49.760 --> 18:51.797
one after
another in cold blood.

18:52.400 --> 18:54.789
I mean, first Watergate
and now this.

18:55.760 --> 18:57.353
What's the world coming to?

19:00.960 --> 19:03.031
Sorry, Mrs. Colson.
Car wouldn't start.

19:03.160 --> 19:05.913
I'll ditch the coat and get
you squared away, okay?

19:07.560 --> 19:08.630
Big night?

19:08.720 --> 19:09.710
Huh?

19:10.120 --> 19:11.554
Got a hangover?

19:11.640 --> 19:12.630
Oh!

19:12.920 --> 19:15.230
No, it's just a migraine.

19:16.560 --> 19:17.709
CONSTANCE: You talk to Ed?

19:18.280 --> 19:19.315
Did I...

19:19.680 --> 19:21.717
About the seminar.
Next weekend?

19:21.800 --> 19:23.791
Got us a room at
the Southnick Hotel.

19:23.880 --> 19:24.950
Oh, yeah.

19:26.000 --> 19:27.911
I don't know.
It's a lot of money.

19:28.640 --> 19:30.995
And we're saving up right now,
so Ed can buy the butcher shop.

19:31.080 --> 19:34.869
What I'm hearing, is you think your
husband's more important than you,

19:34.960 --> 19:36.075
his needs.

19:37.280 --> 19:38.429
No. I just...

19:39.200 --> 19:40.759
We got a plan, you know?

19:40.840 --> 19:44.834
The word "we" is a castle, hon,
with a moat and a drawbridge.

19:44.920 --> 19:46.831
And you know what gets
locked up in castles?

19:48.600 --> 19:50.079
Dragons?

19:50.160 --> 19:51.673
Princesses.

19:51.760 --> 19:53.558
Don't be a prisoner of "we."

19:55.000 --> 19:56.320
Take the seminar.

19:56.960 --> 19:59.156
It'll give you
a key to the castle.

20:00.800 --> 20:01.835
Yeah.

20:05.360 --> 20:08.352
Oh, hey, you don't know what
happened to all the TP, do you?

20:08.440 --> 20:09.430
The what's that?

20:09.560 --> 20:12.313
Had a case of TP in the back
last week. Somebody took it.

20:16.960 --> 20:20.316
LOU: Yes, sir. I know I said
it was a local matter last night,

20:20.400 --> 20:21.799
but I slept on it, you know?

20:21.880 --> 20:26.795
And given the level of violence,
and with no apparent suspects,

20:26.880 --> 20:29.759
and the fact that one of
the victims was a judge...

20:29.840 --> 20:31.239
Right, in North Dakota,

20:31.320 --> 20:33.880
which means you're gonna
have all kinds of interstate issues.

20:34.000 --> 20:38.471
So, my thought is, you know,
all the more reason for me...

20:40.880 --> 20:41.995
Yes, sir.

20:42.560 --> 20:43.675
Thank you, sir.

20:44.240 --> 20:46.072
I'll coordinate
with Sheriff Larsson,

20:46.160 --> 20:47.434
and head up to Fargo
first thing tomorrow.

20:47.520 --> 20:48.510
Yep.

20:52.840 --> 20:54.751
(TYPING IN THE BACKGROUND)

21:02.600 --> 21:03.590
(DOORS CLOSE)

21:04.640 --> 21:05.869
SKIP: Yeah, I know, we...

21:06.400 --> 21:07.799
You said all that,
but my point...

21:09.320 --> 21:10.549
What I'm trying to...

21:12.240 --> 21:14.550
I've got the money, see...
I've got...

21:15.280 --> 21:16.270
Uh...

21:16.360 --> 21:17.430
I...

21:17.520 --> 21:19.238
I mean, I will have.

21:19.320 --> 21:22.870
So, you just need to hold
the Selectrics for me until...

21:23.200 --> 21:24.190
Uh...

21:26.200 --> 21:29.318
So, just hold them, okay?
Don't...

21:30.680 --> 21:32.717
And I'll call you back.

21:34.400 --> 21:35.390
(SIGHS)

21:35.800 --> 21:36.870
Hi, there.

21:37.480 --> 21:38.709
Money troubles?

21:38.800 --> 21:39.835
What?

21:40.400 --> 21:44.633
Oh! No, he double-billed me
for something, is all.

21:44.720 --> 21:47.234
Just straightening
things out.

21:47.600 --> 21:48.590
I see.

21:51.240 --> 21:52.230
Yeah.

21:52.320 --> 21:54.550
We're not really open,
is the thing.

21:55.680 --> 21:58.957
Waitin' for new
models to come in.

21:59.040 --> 22:01.793
So, closed temporarily.

22:04.400 --> 22:05.629
That's okay.

22:05.720 --> 22:07.518
We're not really customers.

22:09.040 --> 22:11.316
Okay, well...

22:11.400 --> 22:12.720
Rye Gerhardt.

22:16.360 --> 22:17.873
Is that your name, or...

22:23.080 --> 22:26.675
I mean, geez,
I met the guy, of course.

22:27.280 --> 22:29.430
Once or twice.

22:30.560 --> 22:31.675
Were you...

22:33.200 --> 22:35.430
Did you need
a character reference or...

22:35.520 --> 22:36.510
(CHUCKLES)

22:37.320 --> 22:38.719
That's good.

22:38.800 --> 22:40.029
I like that.

22:40.120 --> 22:41.474
"A character reference."

22:44.880 --> 22:46.632
How about you just
tell us where he is,

22:46.720 --> 22:48.438
seeing as he
works for you and all.

22:49.880 --> 22:52.156
Well, isn't that what
you told Big Jim Suggs?

22:53.120 --> 22:54.952
Over at the Pig
'n' Poke yesterday?

22:55.600 --> 22:56.874
Had a few drinks.

22:56.960 --> 22:58.633
Told him you had
a Gerhardt in your pocket.

22:58.720 --> 22:59.710
I never...

23:03.040 --> 23:04.838
(TYPEWRITER DINGS)
Ow!

23:07.120 --> 23:08.110
(GRUNTS)

23:10.800 --> 23:12.837
Kids today love to
talk on the phone,

23:13.640 --> 23:15.472
but I'm a big
believer in correspondence,

23:16.160 --> 23:17.958
friendly or otherwise.
(GRUNTS)

23:18.600 --> 23:21.353
"If you've got a complaint,"
is my motto,

23:21.440 --> 23:22.794
"put it in writing."

23:23.800 --> 23:24.870
For instance,

23:24.960 --> 23:26.359
last week I bought
one of those

23:26.440 --> 23:28.954
new automated
coffeemakers at Sears.

23:29.480 --> 23:31.630
You know, the one
with the clock inside?

23:32.320 --> 23:35.039
And the thing is,
pardon my French,

23:35.120 --> 23:36.474
a real piece of shit.

23:37.640 --> 23:38.994
So, what do I do?

23:42.840 --> 23:43.989
(CRACKS FINGERS)

23:47.680 --> 23:51.435
"Dear General Electric,

23:51.520 --> 23:56.549
"the coffee maker that I
bought at Sears on 11th March

23:57.760 --> 23:59.592
"makes a noise when
it's brewing (TYPING)

24:00.360 --> 24:03.557
"That sounds like a fat man
having a heart attack."

24:04.000 --> 24:05.320
(GROANS) Stop!

24:06.720 --> 24:08.870
"And it forces me
to ask the question,

24:10.000 --> 24:13.550
"is this why our once-great
nation IS going down the crapper?

24:16.040 --> 24:17.872
(TYPEWRITER CLANGS)

24:19.960 --> 24:21.553
"Yours in peace and harmony,

24:21.640 --> 24:22.630
(GROANS)

24:22.920 --> 24:24.433
"Mike Milligan."

24:26.840 --> 24:28.114
The judge!

24:28.200 --> 24:29.190
MIKE: Go on.

24:30.720 --> 24:32.677
All I said was talk to her.

24:32.760 --> 24:33.830
What judge?

24:34.400 --> 24:35.754
Mundt!

24:35.840 --> 24:37.274
Judge Mundt!

24:37.800 --> 24:38.790
(CLEARS THROAT)

24:44.560 --> 24:45.834
(WHISPERING)

24:51.680 --> 24:53.159
Talk to her.

24:53.240 --> 24:54.355
That's what you said?

24:55.000 --> 24:56.070
Yeah.

24:56.560 --> 24:57.550
(SCOFFS)

25:11.080 --> 25:12.070
Why?

25:12.920 --> 25:14.069
What happened?

25:14.520 --> 25:15.555
MAN 1: There he goes!

25:15.640 --> 25:17.631
MAN 2:
Don't let him get away, man!

25:17.720 --> 25:19.916
MAN 3: Get a rope
and we'll hang him!

25:30.520 --> 25:33.239
MAN: (SINGING) One hour
ahead of the posse

25:33.320 --> 25:36.073
The bloodhounds
are hot on my trail

25:36.440 --> 25:39.353
Last evening I shot down
my sweetheart

25:39.440 --> 25:42.114
This morning
I broke out of jail

25:42.720 --> 25:45.189
My Pinto is tired and hungry

25:45.560 --> 25:48.029
And I'm feeling weary and gone

25:48.800 --> 25:51.360
We started ahead of the posse

25:51.680 --> 25:54.479
And we got to keep going on

25:54.960 --> 25:57.474
The Sheriff has sworn
he will get me

25:57.800 --> 26:00.519
He's riding with 20 and five

26:01.160 --> 26:03.515
But I ain't afeared
of that posse

26:03.920 --> 26:06.912
For they'll never
will get me alive

26:08.840 --> 26:11.593
One hour ahead of the posse

26:11.680 --> 26:14.832
No turning to left or to right

26:15.000 --> 26:17.469
We must win the race
to the river

26:17.840 --> 26:20.559
Or there'll be
a hanging tonight

26:21.280 --> 26:24.079
We're gonna hang him tonight

26:24.240 --> 26:26.800
One hour ahead of the posse

26:27.200 --> 26:31.114
And now I'm inside on my own

26:34.160 --> 26:38.154
At last we have
beaten that posse

26:38.400 --> 26:39.390
(GUNSHOT)

26:39.840 --> 26:46.837
May the Lord have mercy
on my soul

26:47.880 --> 26:49.393
(PANTING)

28:49.240 --> 28:53.552
BETSY: You said to remind you I got
that specialist appointment Tuesday.

28:54.640 --> 28:55.710
Dad said he'd watch Molly.

28:55.800 --> 28:56.790
I'll drive you.

28:57.720 --> 28:59.279
You sure?
You got the case.

28:59.360 --> 29:00.475
I'll drive you.

29:08.920 --> 29:10.911
We feel so special, don't we?

29:11.000 --> 29:12.399
Gettin' Daddy for lunch.

29:12.840 --> 29:13.875
Daddy!
(CHUCKLES)

29:14.520 --> 29:16.431
Captain said wait
on going up to Fargo.

29:16.520 --> 29:19.831
He needs to work out some
kind of chain of command BS, so...

29:28.600 --> 29:29.635
BETSY: Hon?

29:51.680 --> 29:52.715
Hon?

29:54.040 --> 29:55.155
Sorry.

29:55.800 --> 29:57.199
I got a wild hair.

29:58.720 --> 30:00.119
Something's not adding up.

30:00.840 --> 30:02.114
Stay here, okay?
Uh-huh.

30:05.360 --> 30:06.714
MOLLY: What's Daddy doing?

30:07.880 --> 30:09.029
Work stuff.

30:10.880 --> 30:12.393
You wanna build a showman?

30:13.000 --> 30:14.320
(BELL RINGS)

30:29.720 --> 30:30.994
You wanna build
a snowman?

30:31.080 --> 30:32.309
Can we do it
over there?

30:32.400 --> 30:33.595
How 'bout right here?

30:33.680 --> 30:35.239
Okay, should we
start getting some snow?

30:35.320 --> 30:36.390
Yeah!

30:45.440 --> 30:47.158
What are you gonna
call the snowman, Molly?

30:47.280 --> 30:48.714
Maybe Bob.

31:13.200 --> 31:14.270
Yeah.

31:16.920 --> 31:18.194
BETSY: All right,
we got the bottom.

31:18.280 --> 31:19.998
Next, we need
to make the body.

31:21.240 --> 31:24.073
I need you to find me
some sticks for the arms.

31:24.160 --> 31:25.355
Okay?
Yeah.

31:25.440 --> 31:26.475
Thank you.

31:33.640 --> 31:34.630
(GASPS)

31:38.600 --> 31:39.749
MOLLY: Momma!
Yeah?

31:40.840 --> 31:42.069
Look what I found!

31:46.600 --> 31:47.590
(GRUNTS)

31:55.320 --> 31:56.469
Can I keep it?

32:04.040 --> 32:05.314
No, hon.
It's got a rip.

32:05.440 --> 32:07.431
That's trash now.
Okay?

32:27.680 --> 32:28.829
Okay, okay.

32:29.680 --> 32:30.670
Hon!

32:31.920 --> 32:33.035
Look at this!

32:40.200 --> 32:42.157
Look what I found.
That's great, hon.

32:42.240 --> 32:43.469
BETSY: I found it
in the bushes.

32:43.560 --> 32:45.119
Fingerprints.
BETSY: Yeah, I know.

32:45.200 --> 32:46.793
Jeez, I got it by the barrel.

32:46.880 --> 32:48.029
What's that?

32:48.120 --> 32:50.236
Momma's doing
Daddy's job again.

32:50.360 --> 32:51.794
Go, Mommal!
(CHUCKLES)

32:54.640 --> 32:55.869
You okay, hon?
Yeah.

32:55.960 --> 32:57.314
BETSY: I stood up
too fast, is all.

34:00.840 --> 34:01.955
Help you, Officer?

34:03.040 --> 34:05.714
Sir, please roll up
your window.

34:06.800 --> 34:09.440
My friend up front doesn't
like to talk to strangers.

34:10.159 --> 34:12.071
Well, he's gonna talk to me.

34:16.800 --> 34:17.835
(CROW CAWS)

34:17.920 --> 34:19.797
Rock County.

34:19.880 --> 34:20.915
It's like...

34:21.360 --> 34:23.237
What's that town
on The Flintstones?

34:24.600 --> 34:25.795
Is that where we are?

34:26.480 --> 34:28.197
(SINGING) On the Flintstones?

34:28.280 --> 34:31.591
All right, that's it.
Out of the car, all of you.

34:49.360 --> 34:50.589
Your friends, too.

35:00.000 --> 35:02.230
Come around
the driver's side here.

35:10.240 --> 35:12.800
Okay, let me see some IDs.

35:15.560 --> 35:17.198
I'm gonna reach in my pocket.

35:26.720 --> 35:27.835
Now them.

35:49.080 --> 35:50.150
Mike Milligan

35:51.960 --> 35:53.712
and two named Kitchen.

35:56.640 --> 35:57.675
Brothers, yeah?

35:57.760 --> 35:59.671
MIKE: Yes, sir.
That's us.

36:02.720 --> 36:04.074
Kansas City.

36:05.200 --> 36:07.874
MIKE: What's this about,
Sheriff, if I'm okay to ask?

36:11.520 --> 36:14.672
Now, if I were to search you
three, would I find weapons?

36:15.760 --> 36:17.194
(CHUCKLES) Well, sir.

36:17.280 --> 36:19.556
You have nothin'
to fear from us.

36:19.640 --> 36:22.359
We're just passin' through
town on our way to points south.

36:22.440 --> 36:23.919
Thought we'd stop
for some waffles.

36:24.000 --> 36:25.399
Gale's idea.

36:25.480 --> 36:28.359
Heard you had some
real good ones around here.

36:28.440 --> 36:30.272
So, you can
imagine our surprise

36:30.360 --> 36:34.354
when we find the place closed,
and, apparently, the scene of a crime.

36:37.960 --> 36:39.758
What size shoes you boys wear?

36:40.600 --> 36:42.591
Now, that is
a truly odd question.

36:45.960 --> 36:47.951
Last time I checked,
I was a 10. Boys?

36:54.480 --> 36:56.312
MIKE: Now, I'm gonna go ahead
and guess the boys are an 11,

36:56.440 --> 36:58.829
and not a two, which
would make them toddlers.

36:59.600 --> 37:02.399
Now, unless there's
some law been broken,

37:02.480 --> 37:04.551
I think it's time for
us to be on our way.

37:04.640 --> 37:06.517
I promised the boys' wives
I'd have them home for supper.

37:06.600 --> 37:10.275
And I am, if nothing else,
a man of my word.

37:17.560 --> 37:18.630
Okay.

37:20.160 --> 37:23.471
I got your names
and your plate number.

37:25.080 --> 37:28.835
I'm gonna radio ahead and
make sure you make it out of state.

37:29.680 --> 37:30.670
If not,

37:31.760 --> 37:34.957
I'm gonna put out a APB,
and have you boys rounded up.

37:35.040 --> 37:36.599
And then we'll talk again.

37:37.800 --> 37:39.074
You understand?

37:42.440 --> 37:43.475
MIKE: I do.

37:49.520 --> 37:51.193
And isn't that
a minor miracle?

37:52.240 --> 37:53.514
The state of the world today,

37:53.600 --> 37:56.672
the level of conflict
and misunderstanding,

37:57.680 --> 38:02.197
that two men could stand on
a lonely road in winter and talk,

38:03.040 --> 38:05.839
calmly and rationally.

38:11.160 --> 38:14.949
While all around them
people are losing their mind.

38:29.320 --> 38:30.549
You have a nice day.

38:33.640 --> 38:35.119
(DOORS OPEN)

38:36.400 --> 38:39.233
(DOORS CLOSE
AND ENGINE STARTS)

39:25.120 --> 39:26.838
BUD: Good night, Noreen.
NOREEN: Okay then.

39:32.720 --> 39:33.949
(LAUGHING)

39:48.800 --> 39:49.790
(DOOR CLOSES)

39:49.880 --> 39:52.235
CONSTANCE: Don't be silly.
I'll give you a ride.

39:54.960 --> 39:56.951
PEGGY: You sure?
I don't wanna be a bother.

39:57.080 --> 39:58.400
CONSTANCE: No bother.

39:59.480 --> 40:01.676
CONSTANCE: Come on, sexy.
Get in.

40:05.640 --> 40:07.233
(MUSIC ON CAR STEREO)

40:25.840 --> 40:27.831
(ENGINE STARTS)

40:51.640 --> 40:53.358
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

41:46.120 --> 41:47.679
(CREAKING)

42:15.960 --> 42:17.439
PEGGY:
Right to the right, there.

42:17.520 --> 42:19.477
CONSTANCE: Oonh!
You're a life saver.

42:19.560 --> 42:21.915
It's a real mess.

42:22.000 --> 42:23.149
CONSTANCE: Thanks, doll.

42:23.240 --> 42:25.436
Shouldn't have had
all that ginger ale.

42:25.680 --> 42:27.398
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

42:33.120 --> 42:34.519
(URINATING)

42:45.840 --> 42:46.955
(FLUSHING)

43:34.680 --> 43:35.670
PEGGY: Ed?

43:39.000 --> 43:40.070
(WHISPERS) Ed?

43:40.960 --> 43:42.712
(MUSIC CONTINUES)

43:44.520 --> 43:47.194
MAN: (SINGING) Well,
I might take a plane

43:47.280 --> 43:49.112
Might take a train

43:49.200 --> 43:52.352
If I got to walk,
I'm going just the same

43:52.520 --> 43:54.716
I'm going to Kansas City

43:55.640 --> 43:57.597
Kansas City, here I come

44:00.760 --> 44:02.478
They got some crazy
little women there

44:02.560 --> 44:04.597
Jeez. What happened
to your car?

44:04.680 --> 44:07.320
Oh, no. It's nothing.
Just a dust-up.

44:07.400 --> 44:09.869
Ed had a few too many
last night, and hit a tree.

44:11.320 --> 44:14.119
He's fine though.
Just shook up.

44:14.200 --> 44:15.190
CONSTANCE: What about you?

44:15.280 --> 44:18.033
Me? Oh, no, I wasn't...
I was home.

44:18.120 --> 44:20.555
Those bills aren't
gonna pay themselves.

44:23.080 --> 44:25.310
You're kind of
a bad girl, aren't you?

44:25.400 --> 44:26.435
(SCOFFS)

44:26.520 --> 44:28.272
Yeah, you are.

44:29.200 --> 44:33.034
I'm usually able to tell right
away, but you had me fooled.

44:35.240 --> 44:37.629
Oh, it's nothin'.
I just bumped it, is all.

44:38.760 --> 44:40.433
In the dust-up?

44:40.520 --> 44:42.909
Thought you weren't
in the car, you said.

44:44.480 --> 44:46.949
It's okay. You don't
have to tell the truth.

44:47.800 --> 44:50.314
I'm not even mad
about the TP.

44:50.400 --> 44:52.471
Next time,
just ask though.

44:56.640 --> 44:59.393
Or maybe
that's what you like.

44:59.840 --> 45:00.875
Huh?

45:00.960 --> 45:02.155
Breaking the rules?

45:03.360 --> 45:05.078
Thanks for the ride, okay?

45:05.160 --> 45:08.710
I've just got a real bad
headache, like I said before, and...

45:08.800 --> 45:11.474
So maybe, I'll just see you
at work tomorrow, okay?

45:13.080 --> 45:14.673
Sleep well, now.

45:53.600 --> 45:56.035
Didn't expect
you'd still be here.

45:56.120 --> 45:57.110
Yeah.

45:58.360 --> 46:01.239
Found possibly the murder
weapon over in the bushes there.

46:02.880 --> 46:04.598
Betsy did, I mean,

46:04.680 --> 46:07.832
if I'm being honest,
which I try to be.

46:09.640 --> 46:12.359
So, now I'm wondering
what else I missed.

46:12.440 --> 46:15.114
Anything interesting
on that car I called in?

46:15.400 --> 46:16.435
Oh...

46:16.520 --> 46:19.512
Those fellows were
positively fascinating.

46:20.200 --> 46:22.237
Nothin' actionable, though.

46:22.640 --> 46:23.630
(SIGHS)

46:28.120 --> 46:30.873
Cook fell funny,
is the truth.

46:31.520 --> 46:32.999
Why I'm still here.

46:34.320 --> 46:36.118
Got stuck in my head.

46:37.160 --> 46:38.559
Callback.

46:41.720 --> 46:45.111
Heard it referred to once
as a convergence.

46:45.200 --> 46:47.714
You know, one thing
reminds you of another.

46:47.800 --> 46:48.835
Yeah.

46:53.000 --> 46:54.513
Wanna talk about it?

46:54.600 --> 46:55.954
Not especially.

47:04.960 --> 47:10.478
We had a guy on the boat, liked
to smoke cigars for breakfast.

47:10.560 --> 47:12.995
Picked up the habit
from his grandad, he said.

47:15.920 --> 47:20.790
This was on
the Bode River, '74.

47:24.400 --> 47:27.153
So, I'm on the wheel,
this kid comes out...

47:27.240 --> 47:29.800
"Cause what could he
have been? Nineteen?

47:31.960 --> 47:34.429
Lights his shit stick,
and then...

47:39.920 --> 47:41.957
He never even
saw it coming.

47:43.200 --> 47:45.271
Shot him right
through the cigar.

47:47.680 --> 47:49.637
A one-in-a-million shot.

47:53.120 --> 47:55.714
And the look on his
face when he fell...

47:56.800 --> 47:58.438
Just like the cook.

48:01.040 --> 48:02.474
Bafflement.

48:10.880 --> 48:11.950
Yeah.

48:12.920 --> 48:17.596
This German captain
hung himself.

48:17.680 --> 48:19.114
1945.

48:19.680 --> 48:22.479
Found him in
a bunker during the mop-up,

48:24.200 --> 48:25.793
face all purple,

48:27.160 --> 48:28.753
eyes bugged out.

48:30.600 --> 48:34.958
Then in '62,
I'm responding to a suicide.

48:36.160 --> 48:37.912
Fellow's in his bathroom,

48:39.160 --> 48:41.549
swinging from
an electric cord.

48:46.240 --> 48:47.753
You never know.
Mmm.

48:49.720 --> 48:51.119
War stories.
(CHUCKLES)

48:55.360 --> 48:57.158
Different now, though.

48:58.360 --> 49:01.239
After WWII,

49:01.320 --> 49:06.030
we went six years
without a murder here.

49:06.120 --> 49:07.440
Six years.

49:08.280 --> 49:10.191
Now, these days, well...

49:13.960 --> 49:17.476
Sometimes I wonder if you boys
didn't bring that war home with you.

49:31.040 --> 49:32.792
(MOTOR WHIRRING)

50:01.400 --> 50:03.198
(CAR SLOWING DOWN)

50:56.960 --> 50:58.314
(EXHALES)

51:26.040 --> 51:27.155
(RATTLING)

51:42.960 --> 51:44.553
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

51:53.800 --> 51:55.996
(CONTINUES KNOCKING)

52:01.200 --> 52:03.032
(KNOCKING LOUDER)

52:32.560 --> 52:35.074
LOU: Hey. Burnin' it
at both ends, huh?

52:37.080 --> 52:38.479
Yeah.
Yeah.

52:38.560 --> 52:40.153
Double shift for me.

52:41.360 --> 52:42.919
Yeah. Hear what happened?

52:45.320 --> 52:47.391
At the Waffle Hut? Yeah.
LOU: Yeah.

52:48.120 --> 52:50.350
Real mess.
Yeah.

52:51.360 --> 52:54.637
The killer still
at large, they say?

52:54.720 --> 52:56.393
Yeah, we think so.

52:58.880 --> 53:01.315
Anyway, saw your light on.

53:01.400 --> 53:02.993
You know, Molly loves
bacon for breakfast.

53:03.080 --> 53:04.639
I seem to remember
we're out.

53:04.720 --> 53:06.950
So, I thought, if you don't
mind, I'd pick some up,

53:07.040 --> 53:08.599
be there when she woke up.

53:09.480 --> 53:10.470
(CHUCKLES)

53:10.760 --> 53:11.750
Yeah.
Yeah?

53:11.840 --> 53:13.319
Yeah, sure.
Come on in.

53:16.120 --> 53:17.110
(DOOR CLOSES)

53:17.280 --> 53:18.270
Uh...

53:18.760 --> 53:21.274
So, you want fatback or...

53:21.360 --> 53:22.350
Well, lean,
if you got it.

53:22.440 --> 53:23.475
Okay.

53:23.560 --> 53:24.755
Third of a pound.

53:33.280 --> 53:34.998
So, how's Peggy?

53:35.080 --> 53:36.479
Yeah, she's, uh...

53:37.120 --> 53:41.034
She's doin' good.

53:41.120 --> 53:43.555
You know, doin' real...

53:43.640 --> 53:46.029
Work's good, she says.

